  "impactAssessments": "Defense evasion is a tactic employed by malicious actors to bypass security tools and mechanisms, allowing them to maintain access, escalate privileges, and carry out attacks without being detected (MITRE ATT&CK). \nIt is a critical step in the attack lifecycle because without evading defenses, adversaries cannot effectively execute complex attacks or exfiltrate data. \nThe goal is to operate under the radar of endpoint detection and response (EDR), antivirus (AV), security operations centers (SOC), and other monitoring systems.\n\nAttackers use a variety of methods to achieve defense evasion:\n  Disabling or uninstalling security software to prevent detection. \n  Obfuscating or encrypting scripts and data to hide malicious activity. \n  Abusing trusted processes or legitimate system tools (\u201cliving off the land\u201d) to execute malicious actions without triggering alerts. \n  Fileless malware that runs in memory and avoids writing to disk, making it harder to detect. \n  Privilege escalation bypasses, such as exploiting setuid/setgid bits on Linux/macOS or bypassing User Account Control (UAC) on Windows. \n  Psychological or social evasion, including masquerading malicious websites as legitimate services or sending convincing messages to trick users into providing access.\n\nPlease identify the affected endpoint(smithDesktop) and action related (None).\nUtilize endpoint protection, conduct antivirus scans, and review installed applications.\nRemove suspicious/malicious files and programs. \nScrutinize application settings and add-ons, especially those related to web browsers and freeware.\nDisable redirects and ensure that your applications, particularly web browsers and freeware, are updated to the most recent version. \nInstall apps and add-ons only from trusted sources. \nReview running processes, halt any suspicious/malicious ones, and check for signs of persistence, such as scheduled tasks, registry entries, and WMI.\n\nKeep your system updated and install the most recent updates/upgrades. \n\nEmploy network protection by reviewing inbound/outbound traffic and blocking connections associated with suspicious/malicious activity. \nConsider creating blocking rules and updating policies as needed.\n",
